
GIT HOOKS & GPG SIGNING SETUP
==============================

A lightweight guide to set up local Git hooks and GPG-signed commits
for secure and consistent workflows.

This configuration ensures every commit follows the correct message
format and is cryptographically signed.

------------------------------------------------------------------------
1. Make Git Hooks Executable
------------------------------------------------------------------------

Enable executable permissions for your local Git hooks:

    > chmod +x .githooks/commit-msg
    # Optional:
    # chmod +x .githooks/pre-commit
    # chmod +x .githooks/pre-push

Tell Git to use your local .githooks directory:

    > git config core.hooksPath .githooks

------------------------------------------------------------------------
2. Enable GPG Commit Signing
------------------------------------------------------------------------

a. Set your GPG key

List your available GPG keys:

    > gpg --list-secret-keys --keyid-format LONG

Example output:

    sec   rsa4096/ABCD1234EF567890 2024-05-12 [SC]
          uid [ultimate] Isai Gordeev <isai@example.com>
    sub   rsa4096/XYZ1234567890ABC 2024-05-12 [E]

Use the part after the slash (/) (e.g., ABCD1234EF567890) as your <key-id>.

Then configure Git to use it:

    > git config --global user.signingkey <key-id>
    > git config --global commit.gpgsign true

------------------------------------------------------------------------
3. Verify Hooks and Signing
------------------------------------------------------------------------

Create a test commit:

    > git commit -m "chore(setup): verify gpg signing"

Then check that itâ€™s properly signed:

    > git log --show-signature -1
 
Example output:

    gpg: Signature made Fri  2 Nov 2025 11:42:21 AM UTC
    gpg: Good signature from "Isai Gordeev <isai@gordeev.ru>" [ultimate]

------------------------------------------------------------------------
4. Done
------------------------------------------------------------------------

You now have:

- Local Git hooks for consistent commit formatting
- GPG-signed commits for verified authorship
- A secure, professional Git setup ready for collaborative work
